In Table 3 we focus on the inference for N𝑁N. For each of the three
approaches and for each group of 100 pairs of data sets we report the
average values of the posterior mean of N𝑁N, the estimated coverage of
the 95% credibility intervals and their mean length. Estimated
standard errors are also given in parentheses. Note that in our
approach the average value of the posterior mean for N𝑁N is, in almost
every experimental condition, the closest to the true value N=100𝑁100N=100
and the one with the smallest standard error. However, the reduced
bias of our approach was to be expected because the simulation
generating process is exactly part of our model, while the other
approaches present several misspecification elements. Note also that
the Jaro constrained model and the hybrid approach have different
behaviours, the former overestimating N𝑁N and the latter
underestimating it. This is the same trend already observed in the
multiple block application.
